    - candidate: separate-impact-from-intent (treat feedback as data about your impact, not your intentions)
        - location: lines 1953-1970 (Amplifier 3: Impact Versus Intent), 2149-2162 (Focus on Change from the Inside Out), and the broader Annabelle case (1792-1806, 1957-1970), with the prescriptive script at 1968 ("I've been working hard to be more patient. And yet it sounds like that's not the impact I'm having. That's upsetting. Let's figure out why.").
        - paraphrase: when feedback about your impact contradicts your view of your intentions, the default reaction is to discard the feedback ("but I had good intentions, so the negative impact must not be real or must not be my fault"). The chapter's move: hold the two layers separately. Intentions are yours and you have privileged access to them; impact is theirs and they have privileged access to it. Treat the feedback as data about your impact (which you can't see directly because of leaky face/tone/patterns), not as a verdict on your intentions. The script is "my intent was X. Sounds like the impact was Y. That's upsetting / surprising. Let's figure out why."
        - situation: you have received feedback ("you're difficult," "you're disrespectful," "you bossed me around") that you can't reconcile with your sense of what you were trying to do. You are about to either reject the feedback ("that's not who I am, I had good intentions") or accept it and abandon your own sense of your intentions ("I guess I really am that bad").
        - outcome: → promoted to separate-impact-from-intent. Folds in the leaky-face/tone/patterns category (your behavior is in their awareness and not yours, so their impact-data is your only access to the gap). Folds in the change-from-inside-out point (changing only behavior while leaving feelings intact produces leak; changing the feeling is the deeper move once the impact data has landed). Distinct from separate-data-from-interpretation (that decomposes a giver's verdict into data + interpretation about *you*; this decomposes *your own action* into intent + impact and centers the receiver-side asymmetry of access). Distinct from difference-spot-not-wrong-spot (that surfaces differences in observed data and applied interpretation; this surfaces the structural asymmetry between intent-access and impact-access).

